WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.900 --> 00:00:08.820
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:12.820 --> 00:00:13.570
INTERVIEWER: Good.

00:00:13.570 --> 00:00:14.650
Hello.

00:00:14.650 --> 00:00:16.840
Maybe you'd like to introduce
yourself and tell us

00:00:16.840 --> 00:00:20.900
what led you to working at the
university a couple of years

00:00:20.900 --> 00:00:21.400
ago.

00:00:21.400 --> 00:00:24.360
SUKI KIM: Well, I was born
and raised in South Korea,

00:00:24.360 --> 00:00:27.190
and I moved to
America in my teens.

00:00:27.190 --> 00:00:31.260
And I do actually come from--
there's a personal history.

00:00:31.260 --> 00:00:34.360
The Korean War did
separate my family,

00:00:34.360 --> 00:00:37.780
and some members ended up
being taken to North Korea.

00:00:37.780 --> 00:00:38.990
This is not that unusual.

00:00:38.990 --> 00:00:41.350
It actually happened
to a lot of people.

00:00:41.350 --> 00:00:43.880
They estimate like a
million plus families were

00:00:43.880 --> 00:00:46.470
affected by that back in 1953.

00:00:46.470 --> 00:00:51.100
And having grown up with
that separation and sorrow,

00:00:51.100 --> 00:00:54.580
then I became an immigrant
to going to America

00:00:54.580 --> 00:00:57.540
in my teens, where I didn't
speak a word of English.

00:00:57.540 --> 00:01:00.880
So I think that that
really was a big issue.

00:01:00.880 --> 00:01:04.739
And then I went to North
Korea by chance in 2002

00:01:04.739 --> 00:01:05.970
for the first time.

00:01:05.970 --> 00:01:09.370
And then I realized there was
this world that was basically

00:01:09.370 --> 00:01:11.880
a wound, heartbreak
for Korean people

00:01:11.880 --> 00:01:16.170
that is not being explained
in a way we can understand.

00:01:16.170 --> 00:01:17.650
I kept going back in.

00:01:17.650 --> 00:01:21.110
And there's no way you can go
find out about North Korea,

00:01:21.110 --> 00:01:23.550
except seeing the
government's propaganda.

00:01:23.550 --> 00:01:25.010
You will just never see it.

00:01:25.010 --> 00:01:27.105
So what that meant was--
and I went five times

00:01:27.105 --> 00:01:28.410
through a decade.

00:01:28.410 --> 00:01:30.610
And what that
meant was you would

00:01:30.610 --> 00:01:34.940
have to go undercover and be
really embedded there in a way.

00:01:34.940 --> 00:01:37.160
So I found out about
the school, which was

00:01:37.160 --> 00:01:39.930
run by Evangelical Christians.

00:01:39.930 --> 00:01:43.300
So I ended up
posing as a teacher,

00:01:43.300 --> 00:01:46.404
posing as an
Evangelical Christian.

00:01:46.404 --> 00:01:47.820
INTERVIEWER: So
the university was

00:01:47.820 --> 00:01:49.700
run by Evangelical
Christians who

00:01:49.700 --> 00:01:51.480
were sort of undercover
in the country,

00:01:51.480 --> 00:01:53.230
and you were an
undercover teacher, just

00:01:53.230 --> 00:01:55.490
layers of undercover.

00:01:55.490 --> 00:01:57.800
SUKI KIM: Well, it's a
very complicated situation

00:01:57.800 --> 00:01:59.210
to try to explain, obviously.

00:01:59.210 --> 00:02:02.450
Because this group of
fundamental Evangelical

00:02:02.450 --> 00:02:05.440
Christians that fund
the school-- $35 million

00:02:05.440 --> 00:02:09.300
to build and a lot
more to operate--

00:02:09.300 --> 00:02:12.730
they have made a deal, some
sort of an official deal,

00:02:12.730 --> 00:02:14.180
to not proselytize.

00:02:14.180 --> 00:02:17.740
They'll go there and build the
school-- because proselytizing

00:02:17.740 --> 00:02:19.610
is an execution of a crime.

00:02:19.610 --> 00:02:22.850
And we have seen that, where
people get detained there.

00:02:22.850 --> 00:02:24.050
But those are different.

00:02:24.050 --> 00:02:25.633
The ones who get
detained are the ones

00:02:25.633 --> 00:02:27.740
who went in there
under tourist visa.

00:02:27.740 --> 00:02:30.240
These are the people who go to
North Korea on a tourist visa

00:02:30.240 --> 00:02:32.390
and take videos and
put it on YouTube.

00:02:32.390 --> 00:02:33.840
There's a lot of actually these.

00:02:33.840 --> 00:02:35.839
You just pay money, and
you can go as a tourist.

00:02:35.839 --> 00:02:38.140
It's not a big deal to go
to North Korea that way.

00:02:38.140 --> 00:02:40.330
But then they're
passing bibles out.

00:02:40.330 --> 00:02:44.010
So those people will be
detained, no question about it.

00:02:44.010 --> 00:02:48.040
But the group I was with
was working with the regime,

00:02:48.040 --> 00:02:49.680
cooperating with the regime.

00:02:49.680 --> 00:02:52.310
The whole deal was they're
going to basically fund

00:02:52.310 --> 00:02:55.390
the education of the future
leaders of North Korea,

00:02:55.390 --> 00:02:58.640
hoping one day they
will be converted.

00:02:58.640 --> 00:03:00.860
A perfect population,
really, because it's actually

00:03:00.860 --> 00:03:04.350
a very, very devoutly faithful
people to their cause--

00:03:04.350 --> 00:03:05.730
I mean the great leader.

00:03:05.730 --> 00:03:08.920
So when that great leader
falls, they will actually

00:03:08.920 --> 00:03:11.670
convert to the next religion.

00:03:11.670 --> 00:03:15.120
So they made that deal So
they are not-- the regime

00:03:15.120 --> 00:03:16.830
knows exactly who they are.

00:03:16.830 --> 00:03:18.790
They just do not proselytize.

00:03:18.790 --> 00:03:21.390
So it's just not
out in the open.

00:03:21.390 --> 00:03:26.010
So when I went in there
with them, I was, I guess,

00:03:26.010 --> 00:03:29.610
posing as one of
them, but also they

00:03:29.610 --> 00:03:31.950
were kind of posing as
not being Christians

00:03:31.950 --> 00:03:33.370
when they were out in the open.

00:03:33.370 --> 00:03:36.211
So it was a very
double situation.

00:03:36.211 --> 00:03:38.710
INTERVIEWER: And this line, I
think what I got from the book

00:03:38.710 --> 00:03:43.230
was that the students are
very apt at lying as well.

00:03:43.230 --> 00:03:46.340
They're very good at lying, and
they lied to you constantly,

00:03:46.340 --> 00:03:46.840
almost.

00:03:46.840 --> 00:03:50.360
And so it just felt, with the
students lying and the teachers

00:03:50.360 --> 00:03:52.940
lying and you lying, it just
felt like a lot of lies.

00:03:52.940 --> 00:03:54.940
SUKI KIM: Truth and lies
was really a big theme.

00:03:54.940 --> 00:03:58.440
It's interesting, because I just
gave a TED Talk in Vancouver.

00:03:58.440 --> 00:04:01.140
And the theme of
this year was where

00:04:01.140 --> 00:04:04.350
the Google founder
was, supposedly,

00:04:04.350 --> 00:04:07.240
somewhere in the crowd.

00:04:07.240 --> 00:04:08.950
But their big theme
was truth and lie,

00:04:08.950 --> 00:04:10.900
and that's the talk I gave.

00:04:10.900 --> 00:04:15.815
And it's because the whole
world is built on lies.

00:04:15.815 --> 00:04:19.660
The entire system of the great
leader, this entire country

00:04:19.660 --> 00:04:22.430
runs according to the
myth of the great leader.

00:04:22.430 --> 00:04:26.540
And if that is a lie, then where
do you begin to know the truth?

00:04:26.540 --> 00:04:29.590
And in order to
discover the truth,

00:04:29.590 --> 00:04:33.140
I also had to pretend to be
something I'm not in order

00:04:33.140 --> 00:04:34.550
to get to the truth.

00:04:34.550 --> 00:04:36.490
So the question
of truth and lies

00:04:36.490 --> 00:04:38.550
does become a really
important theme

00:04:38.550 --> 00:04:42.210
when you do more and
more, I guess, research,

00:04:42.210 --> 00:04:44.360
into the topic of North Korea.

00:04:44.360 --> 00:04:45.110
INTERVIEWER: Cool.

00:04:45.110 --> 00:04:46.515
And so who were the peoples
that you were teaching for--

00:04:46.515 --> 00:04:49.135
SUKI KIM: It ended up being--
I didn't know this going in.

00:04:49.135 --> 00:04:54.340
In 2011, which was
Juche year 100.

00:04:54.340 --> 00:04:57.570
What that means is they
count the calendars.

00:04:57.570 --> 00:04:59.870
Juche is North Korea's
foundational philosophy,

00:04:59.870 --> 00:05:02.665
meaning self-reliance,
which is why

00:05:02.665 --> 00:05:04.040
they're so isolated,
because they

00:05:04.040 --> 00:05:07.380
don't rely on anybody else.

00:05:07.380 --> 00:05:09.170
They also count
the calendar system

00:05:09.170 --> 00:05:14.320
according to their original
great leader's birth,

00:05:14.320 --> 00:05:15.840
so their calendar was different.

00:05:15.840 --> 00:05:22.020
So 2011 was actually Juche year
100, although he died in 1994.

00:05:22.020 --> 00:05:25.770
To celebrate his birthday,
despite the fact he died,

00:05:25.770 --> 00:05:30.670
they shut down every
university across North Korea

00:05:30.670 --> 00:05:33.290
and sent all the
university students

00:05:33.290 --> 00:05:38.400
into construction fields to
build North Korea's biggest

00:05:38.400 --> 00:05:41.872
idea, which is a powerful
and prosperous nation, which

00:05:41.872 --> 00:05:43.080
is what they call themselves.

00:05:43.080 --> 00:05:47.060
To build that, they sent all
the kids to construction fields,

00:05:47.060 --> 00:05:51.380
except 270 young men, who
are the sons of the elite.

00:05:51.380 --> 00:05:55.240
And those were the boys--
I mean, they're 19 and 20.

00:05:55.240 --> 00:05:57.610
But those were the young
men I ended up living

00:05:57.610 --> 00:06:00.590
with in this private location
where nobody was allowed out

00:06:00.590 --> 00:06:01.215
of the premise.

00:06:04.802 --> 00:06:06.760
INTERVIEWER: So what did
you discuss with them?

00:06:06.760 --> 00:06:08.060
You were teaching them English.

00:06:08.060 --> 00:06:09.559
It was a science
university, but you

00:06:09.559 --> 00:06:10.850
weren't teaching them science.

00:06:10.850 --> 00:06:13.230
And what was sort of the
day-to-day interactions

00:06:13.230 --> 00:06:13.785
with them?

00:06:13.785 --> 00:06:14.140
What would you--

00:06:14.140 --> 00:06:14.210
SUKI KIM: No.

00:06:14.210 --> 00:06:16.126
I mean, this just goes
back to the whole truth

00:06:16.126 --> 00:06:16.890
and lies question.

00:06:16.890 --> 00:06:19.150
It's a university of
science and technology,

00:06:19.150 --> 00:06:21.410
but there were no
science teachers.

00:06:21.410 --> 00:06:23.530
A lot of their
majors were computer,

00:06:23.530 --> 00:06:26.430
but they didn't know the
existence of the internet.

00:06:26.430 --> 00:06:30.980
So I did see people,
actually-- towards the end,

00:06:30.980 --> 00:06:36.540
they showed me a student
with a Google page, actually,

00:06:36.540 --> 00:06:39.400
and he was Googling something.

00:06:39.400 --> 00:06:43.480
But when you talked to him
afterward, they didn't know.

00:06:43.480 --> 00:06:46.150
They would ask questions
like, how many movies can you

00:06:46.150 --> 00:06:47.760
watch on the internet?

00:06:47.760 --> 00:06:50.630
And how long is a movie that
you see on the internet?

00:06:50.630 --> 00:06:52.660
Like that kind of questions.

00:06:52.660 --> 00:06:56.370
Clearly they're not
on the internet.

00:06:56.370 --> 00:07:01.880
So this was sort of the daily
existence of that school.

00:07:01.880 --> 00:07:04.620
Everything was watched 24/7.

00:07:04.620 --> 00:07:10.300
Minders lived in the same
building as the teachers.

00:07:10.300 --> 00:07:14.080
Counterparts were
people who oversaw

00:07:14.080 --> 00:07:17.800
all the lesson plans because you
had to get everything approved.

00:07:17.800 --> 00:07:21.550
Every class was recorded
and reported on.

00:07:21.550 --> 00:07:24.970
I had meals three times
a day with the students,

00:07:24.970 --> 00:07:28.410
and it's me and three
students at each table.

00:07:28.410 --> 00:07:31.850
And that conversation
was reported on,

00:07:31.850 --> 00:07:34.900
because they were
watching each other.

00:07:34.900 --> 00:07:38.600
So they have these critique
meetings at least once a week,

00:07:38.600 --> 00:07:41.530
where they then report
on what they've heard,

00:07:41.530 --> 00:07:43.260
what they have witnessed.

00:07:43.260 --> 00:07:47.120
So there wasn't a
single place you could

00:07:47.120 --> 00:07:50.620
be where you had any privacy.

00:07:50.620 --> 00:07:52.030
And I taught English.

00:07:52.030 --> 00:07:55.420
That's the only subject that
got taught in that school.

00:07:55.420 --> 00:07:59.280
But, basically, their
schedules were mapped out.

00:07:59.280 --> 00:08:01.430
So they did tons and tons
of great leader duties

00:08:01.430 --> 00:08:03.080
and great leader studies.

00:08:03.080 --> 00:08:05.260
And then they learned English.

00:08:05.260 --> 00:08:08.410
And it was just
repetition of that.

00:08:08.410 --> 00:08:11.190
It was a soldier-like
existence for them.

00:08:11.190 --> 00:08:12.940
INTERVIEWER: How much
of the outside world

00:08:12.940 --> 00:08:14.550
could you discuss with them?

00:08:14.550 --> 00:08:15.840
Did you try and sort of--

00:08:15.840 --> 00:08:18.310
SUKI KIM: There were rules
and rules, as you can imagine.

00:08:18.310 --> 00:08:20.460
The rules and rules
just went on and on.

00:08:20.460 --> 00:08:23.270
And they just went from, you
know, you couldn't wear jeans,

00:08:23.270 --> 00:08:26.240
because Kim Jong-il
really hated jeans,

00:08:26.240 --> 00:08:30.300
because they were a symbol
of America, so not allowed

00:08:30.300 --> 00:08:32.809
in that country.

00:08:32.809 --> 00:08:37.120
But things like, do
not compare ever.

00:08:37.120 --> 00:08:39.590
Like you wouldn't
say, oh, it's amazing.

00:08:39.590 --> 00:08:41.900
It's like this, because
back home, in my country,

00:08:41.900 --> 00:08:44.530
like, that's not allowed.

00:08:44.530 --> 00:08:46.170
Don't ever suggest
there's anything

00:08:46.170 --> 00:08:49.150
wrong with their
country was another one.

00:08:49.150 --> 00:08:51.380
Never, ever discuss
the outside world.

00:08:51.380 --> 00:08:54.320
Do not ever talk to
somebody outside when

00:08:54.320 --> 00:08:57.840
you're taken on a trip outside,
which teachers were taken

00:08:57.840 --> 00:09:04.250
on trips on weekend, just to
get groceries, or great leaders

00:09:04.250 --> 00:09:06.110
buildings, because
every building is

00:09:06.110 --> 00:09:07.700
about a great leader
in North Korea.

00:09:07.700 --> 00:09:10.840
So there were all
these rules to follow,

00:09:10.840 --> 00:09:15.200
so there was nothing you could
talk about the outside world.

00:09:15.200 --> 00:09:18.580
But when you live with
someone for months and months

00:09:18.580 --> 00:09:23.430
and months, and as a teacher,
where I could assign things,

00:09:23.430 --> 00:09:26.020
with an approval that
I assigned letters.

00:09:26.020 --> 00:09:29.620
I assigned essay writing
and compositions.

00:09:29.620 --> 00:09:34.830
Through those things and also
daily conversation over meals,

00:09:34.830 --> 00:09:38.620
things start slipping out
and escaping, and thoughts.

00:09:38.620 --> 00:09:40.340
It was really more thoughts.

00:09:40.340 --> 00:09:43.414
And the people asked me, did
you see North Koreans starving?

00:09:43.414 --> 00:09:44.830
And I don't know
why people are so

00:09:44.830 --> 00:09:46.560
curious about that,
because we know

00:09:46.560 --> 00:09:50.280
there's an 80% food shortage.

00:09:50.280 --> 00:09:52.700
I don't think that's
what was fascinating.

00:09:52.700 --> 00:09:58.320
You know, yes, I was taken out
of Pyongyang on a school bus.

00:09:58.320 --> 00:10:02.040
And you can guess those
things from looking

00:10:02.040 --> 00:10:04.806
at the really, really
malnourished people out

00:10:04.806 --> 00:10:05.940
in the distance.

00:10:05.940 --> 00:10:07.750
They're not going to
let you talk to them,

00:10:07.750 --> 00:10:09.370
but you can see that.

00:10:09.370 --> 00:10:12.200
But I think it's more
what this kind of society

00:10:12.200 --> 00:10:15.320
does to an individual
psychologically, I think,

00:10:15.320 --> 00:10:17.980
is more what I was
there to find out,

00:10:17.980 --> 00:10:22.940
which did become-- as we were
bonding, me and my students,

00:10:22.940 --> 00:10:27.787
more and more, I think I did get
glimpses of their world more.

00:10:27.787 --> 00:10:29.370
INTERVIEWER: I think
what surprised me

00:10:29.370 --> 00:10:32.620
about reading the book
was how even the elite,

00:10:32.620 --> 00:10:35.600
they fear the society, and
they play by the rules.

00:10:35.600 --> 00:10:38.570
I think I'd assumed that those
nearly perhaps knew the game,

00:10:38.570 --> 00:10:40.470
knew what was
going on, and would

00:10:40.470 --> 00:10:41.840
be able to speak more freely.

00:10:41.840 --> 00:10:43.531
But they weren't able to.

00:10:43.531 --> 00:10:44.030
They--

00:10:44.030 --> 00:10:47.150
SUKI KIM: I think it's amazing
how, in the rest of the world,

00:10:47.150 --> 00:10:48.970
we get these reports
of North Koreans

00:10:48.970 --> 00:10:51.960
are all sneaking DVDs
and watching soap operas,

00:10:51.960 --> 00:10:54.440
and they're all
like on cell phones.

00:10:54.440 --> 00:10:57.320
And that I didn't see.

00:10:57.320 --> 00:10:59.440
Even if they did
not show that to me,

00:10:59.440 --> 00:11:02.200
I didn't see how that
was going on so rampantly

00:11:02.200 --> 00:11:03.900
in that country,
because what I saw

00:11:03.900 --> 00:11:08.350
was such a tight control and
such a lack of knowledge.

00:11:08.350 --> 00:11:12.460
Even if they saw some
forbidden video somewhere,

00:11:12.460 --> 00:11:14.260
it's very clear to
me they just had

00:11:14.260 --> 00:11:17.140
no concept of how--
for example, we all

00:11:17.140 --> 00:11:20.879
had to-- in the Korean
culture, you make kimchi.

00:11:20.879 --> 00:11:23.170
I don't know if you guys know
that that's a Korean dish

00:11:23.170 --> 00:11:24.730
that every family eats.

00:11:24.730 --> 00:11:27.200
And we make this massive
kimchi in November, and which

00:11:27.200 --> 00:11:28.800
North Koreans do, too.

00:11:28.800 --> 00:11:32.840
And we all peeled
garlics together.

00:11:32.840 --> 00:11:35.770
But this was actually where
it was really complex,

00:11:35.770 --> 00:11:38.860
because I felt like, that
age, 19-year-old college

00:11:38.860 --> 00:11:41.700
students, boys,
to get all of them

00:11:41.700 --> 00:11:45.730
to peel garlic so diligently
would be very hard in America.

00:11:45.730 --> 00:11:47.080
I don't know about England.

00:11:47.080 --> 00:11:49.420
But that would be
nearly impossible.

00:11:49.420 --> 00:11:54.560
But they were so really
earnestly peeling garlic.

00:11:54.560 --> 00:11:57.440
Because there, they said, if
we all make kimchi together,

00:11:57.440 --> 00:11:59.040
it would be quicker.

00:11:59.040 --> 00:12:02.516
So those were, I think, positive
moments of what I observed.

00:12:02.516 --> 00:12:04.390
Even if that's obedience,
there was something

00:12:04.390 --> 00:12:06.350
that was really heartwarming.

00:12:06.350 --> 00:12:08.820
But at the same time,
they would ask me things

00:12:08.820 --> 00:12:11.970
like-- we had this really
lovely moment where they then

00:12:11.970 --> 00:12:12.882
began discussing.

00:12:12.882 --> 00:12:14.590
Because it's a family
tradition in Korea.

00:12:14.590 --> 00:12:17.410
Everybody makes kimchi
together in November.

00:12:17.410 --> 00:12:19.330
And they said, you
know, their family

00:12:19.330 --> 00:12:23.966
gets like 8 kilos of cabbages
delivered from the government.

00:12:23.966 --> 00:12:25.840
And then depending on
the size of the family,

00:12:25.840 --> 00:12:29.930
another family gets 12 kilos
of cabbages, government sends.

00:12:29.930 --> 00:12:32.880
And he said to me-- actually
the group of them asked me.

00:12:32.880 --> 00:12:35.270
They said, so what
about you, Professor?

00:12:35.270 --> 00:12:37.175
How many kilos does
your government

00:12:37.175 --> 00:12:39.600
send-- cabbages
do they send you?

00:12:39.600 --> 00:12:42.730
And I was like, you know,
in Manhattan, [CHUCKLES]

00:12:42.730 --> 00:12:46.680
where I live, no, the New
York City government is not

00:12:46.680 --> 00:12:48.990
sending me cabbages to
make kimchi every November.

00:12:48.990 --> 00:12:52.480
And I think it was moments like
that where I thought, you know,

00:12:52.480 --> 00:12:53.430
this is not faking.

00:12:53.430 --> 00:12:55.050
This is not a
government propaganda.

00:12:55.050 --> 00:12:56.770
They really have no idea.

00:12:56.770 --> 00:12:58.950
And there were a lot
of moments like that,

00:12:58.950 --> 00:13:02.970
which does make you realize
the-- and these were

00:13:02.970 --> 00:13:04.720
the best and brightest.

00:13:04.720 --> 00:13:07.740
And so there were a lot of
moments like that where it just

00:13:07.740 --> 00:13:09.680
was a different way.

00:13:09.680 --> 00:13:11.290
And they were not
getting information

00:13:11.290 --> 00:13:13.160
about the outside world.

00:13:13.160 --> 00:13:14.990
INTERVIEWER: So the
campus that you were on

00:13:14.990 --> 00:13:17.580
was-- I think one of things I
picked out that it was guarded

00:13:17.580 --> 00:13:20.685
by female guards, which I
would have thoughts putting 19

00:13:20.685 --> 00:13:24.610
and 20-year-old young man
with their female equivalents

00:13:24.610 --> 00:13:26.675
would've been a
recipe for disaster.

00:13:26.675 --> 00:13:27.880
But it didn't?

00:13:27.880 --> 00:13:29.450
SUKI KIM: It didn't, actually.

00:13:29.450 --> 00:13:31.120
I mean, as far as I know.

00:13:31.120 --> 00:13:33.030
I didn't see them ever mixing.

00:13:33.030 --> 00:13:35.890
And those women never
talked back to me.

00:13:35.890 --> 00:13:37.906
I basically don't
really know what

00:13:37.906 --> 00:13:39.280
the girls are like
in North Korea

00:13:39.280 --> 00:13:43.580
because my only point of
reference were these boys.

00:13:43.580 --> 00:13:46.960
And from what I understand,
what I understood,

00:13:46.960 --> 00:13:50.940
because I was very curious
about that, that supposedly

00:13:50.940 --> 00:13:53.350
the school-- why the schools
are allowed to be built

00:13:53.350 --> 00:13:55.940
is really many, many reasons,
obviously, one of which

00:13:55.940 --> 00:13:57.550
is government propaganda.

00:13:57.550 --> 00:14:00.370
So that the foreign
media that can come in

00:14:00.370 --> 00:14:03.130
for a couple of days and film
the school, and the school

00:14:03.130 --> 00:14:04.920
looks fantastic,
and the kids look

00:14:04.920 --> 00:14:08.010
really healthy and beautiful.

00:14:08.010 --> 00:14:11.050
Then they can turn around
and say North Korea looks

00:14:11.050 --> 00:14:13.060
like this, which it does not.

00:14:13.060 --> 00:14:15.540
So when they did get
male soldiers there

00:14:15.540 --> 00:14:20.340
to guard the place, I don't know
what they need guarding from

00:14:20.340 --> 00:14:22.767
or to, because obviously
we're just not allowed out.

00:14:22.767 --> 00:14:24.350
So I felt like it
was the guard's work

00:14:24.350 --> 00:14:25.930
to make sure we did not escape.

00:14:25.930 --> 00:14:27.530
Actually, they were
not protecting us.

00:14:27.530 --> 00:14:29.240
I mean, it the other way around.

00:14:29.240 --> 00:14:33.500
But they basically
didn't want men soldiers,

00:14:33.500 --> 00:14:36.200
because they said it looked
too threatening, whereas women

00:14:36.200 --> 00:14:39.710
soldiers are not threatening
to foreign eyes, supposedly.

00:14:39.710 --> 00:14:41.010
So that was a reason.

00:14:41.010 --> 00:14:43.440
And another reason nothing
happened between the boys

00:14:43.440 --> 00:14:46.290
and the girls is because
there is such a class

00:14:46.290 --> 00:14:47.550
difference in North Korea.

00:14:47.550 --> 00:14:50.970
It's called songbun, and the
family difference, basically

00:14:50.970 --> 00:14:54.100
the girls came from much
lower class than the boys,

00:14:54.100 --> 00:14:56.850
and they just would not be
interested in each other.

00:14:56.850 --> 00:14:59.820
They're not the kind of
people who mix in that world.

00:14:59.820 --> 00:15:01.709
So that's what I
understood it to be.

00:15:01.709 --> 00:15:03.500
INTERVIEWER: And what
was your relationship

00:15:03.500 --> 00:15:05.960
like with the minders,
those who were sort

00:15:05.960 --> 00:15:07.440
of watching over what you did?

00:15:07.440 --> 00:15:10.180
And as an extension,
how much did you

00:15:10.180 --> 00:15:12.850
feel watched, your emails,
your phone calls and so forth?

00:15:12.850 --> 00:15:15.470
SUKI KIM: Well, you just--
you know, being in North Korea

00:15:15.470 --> 00:15:17.380
is just a constant surveillance.

00:15:17.380 --> 00:15:20.140
So I don't know if
there was a camera.

00:15:20.140 --> 00:15:22.270
I definitely it was
tapped because they

00:15:22.270 --> 00:15:23.890
would know the conversations.

00:15:23.890 --> 00:15:27.410
Or the minders, we were told
there are-- the teachers

00:15:27.410 --> 00:15:29.680
had email and internet.

00:15:29.680 --> 00:15:31.880
The students didn't
even know what it was.

00:15:31.880 --> 00:15:34.330
So even though our dorms were
right next to each other,

00:15:34.330 --> 00:15:36.380
we were in a different
world, really.

00:15:36.380 --> 00:15:39.590
And our emails, the
teachers' emails,

00:15:39.590 --> 00:15:44.140
we were told by the
administrators of the school

00:15:44.140 --> 00:15:47.140
who were running the school,
told us to basically set up

00:15:47.140 --> 00:15:49.620
a different email when
you go into North Korea,

00:15:49.620 --> 00:15:52.300
because they can really
easily go into your accounts

00:15:52.300 --> 00:15:52.820
and stuff.

00:15:52.820 --> 00:15:55.650
And you don't really want them
to have all of your friends

00:15:55.650 --> 00:15:58.360
emails, too. [CHUCKLES] I
feel like my friends would

00:15:58.360 --> 00:16:02.830
have all disowned me if
their privacy was jeopardized

00:16:02.830 --> 00:16:03.560
like that.

00:16:03.560 --> 00:16:07.700
So in these emails
that you sent home,

00:16:07.700 --> 00:16:10.010
we were told to just
keep it minimum so

00:16:10.010 --> 00:16:11.625
that people know you're safe.

00:16:11.625 --> 00:16:15.420
But the minders knew it
was a monitored connection.

00:16:15.420 --> 00:16:19.840
So I would say, for example,
I woke up today at 4:00 AM,

00:16:19.840 --> 00:16:20.420
whatever.

00:16:20.420 --> 00:16:22.381
And then the minder
would repeat that to me.

00:16:22.381 --> 00:16:24.880
He would say, oh, so did you
get up at 4:00 AM this morning?

00:16:24.880 --> 00:16:26.500
You must be tired.

00:16:26.500 --> 00:16:31.630
So that does just wipe
out any sense of that--

00:16:31.630 --> 00:16:33.884
and another thing
I realized there.

00:16:33.884 --> 00:16:35.800
You know, they do have
letters in North Korea,

00:16:35.800 --> 00:16:38.260
for example, letter
system, postal system.

00:16:38.260 --> 00:16:39.900
But when I talked
to my students,

00:16:39.900 --> 00:16:41.766
they didn't really
know what letters were.

00:16:41.766 --> 00:16:43.140
They didn't know
how to write it.

00:16:43.140 --> 00:16:44.880
They didn't really send them.

00:16:44.880 --> 00:16:48.330
And I realized these
communication methods,

00:16:48.330 --> 00:16:49.730
we need privacy.

00:16:49.730 --> 00:16:52.000
Letters do lose meaning.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:55.580
Emails do lose meaning when
everybody else can see it.

00:16:55.580 --> 00:16:57.460
Or it's like the
authority that can

00:16:57.460 --> 00:16:59.320
punish you is
looking it over, then

00:16:59.320 --> 00:17:01.920
that means of communication
loses that meaning.

00:17:01.920 --> 00:17:04.859
And that was a very--
you know, having--

00:17:04.859 --> 00:17:06.680
even for teachers
having email access

00:17:06.680 --> 00:17:10.161
wasn't really the same as
having email access here.

00:17:10.161 --> 00:17:11.619
INTERVIEWER: I
quite like the story

00:17:11.619 --> 00:17:16.390
where you were very keen to
get in to watch "Harry Potter."

00:17:16.390 --> 00:17:18.760
And there was an argument
with the teachers

00:17:18.760 --> 00:17:21.400
who wanted to show them "The
Chronicles of Narnia" again.

00:17:21.400 --> 00:17:23.240
And I liked that the--
perhaps you could

00:17:23.240 --> 00:17:25.750
talk about the differences
with the other teachers there

00:17:25.750 --> 00:17:28.430
and also why the peoples were so
keen to watch the Harry Potter

00:17:28.430 --> 00:17:31.320
film that connected
them to the world.

00:17:31.320 --> 00:17:32.810
SUKI KIM: I mean,
it's not-- sorry.

00:17:32.810 --> 00:17:34.226
I don't want you
to misunderstand.

00:17:34.226 --> 00:17:38.460
It's not like I'm a-- I mean,
I'm not a "Harry Potter" fan.

00:17:38.460 --> 00:17:43.250
But my students just did
not have access to anything.

00:17:43.250 --> 00:17:43.825
None.

00:17:43.825 --> 00:17:45.120
They were not allowed out.

00:17:45.120 --> 00:17:46.960
They were not allowed to keep
in touch with their family.

00:17:46.960 --> 00:17:47.790
They had nothing.

00:17:47.790 --> 00:17:49.814
Basically I'm the
only thing they had,

00:17:49.814 --> 00:17:51.230
I realized more
and more and more.

00:17:51.230 --> 00:17:53.090
I really felt
motherly towards them.

00:17:53.090 --> 00:17:55.910
And they, one by
one, towards the end,

00:17:55.910 --> 00:17:59.030
kept asking me about Harry
and Ron and Hermione.

00:17:59.030 --> 00:18:03.470
And I was like, did these
kids-- where did you learn this?

00:18:03.470 --> 00:18:07.480
And it only is because
in that school,

00:18:07.480 --> 00:18:11.000
the textbook was chosen very
carefully that was approved.

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:14.914
But it was an old dated textbook
that was once used in China.

00:18:14.914 --> 00:18:17.080
So anything that was used
in China, the North Korean

00:18:17.080 --> 00:18:18.230
government let it go.

00:18:18.230 --> 00:18:20.630
It was very, very dated.

00:18:20.630 --> 00:18:24.220
But you know those ESL
textbooks have little passages.

00:18:24.220 --> 00:18:25.931
And in those passages
were so dated,

00:18:25.931 --> 00:18:27.930
they would talk about
like, paying for something

00:18:27.930 --> 00:18:31.340
with a $2 personal check in
the US, and things like that.

00:18:31.340 --> 00:18:33.020
And I would have to
just say, actually,

00:18:33.020 --> 00:18:34.670
we don't do that anymore.

00:18:34.670 --> 00:18:37.850
But they actually talked
about "Harry Potter" in one

00:18:37.850 --> 00:18:39.180
of those textbooks, supposedly.

00:18:39.180 --> 00:18:43.490
And because they had so little,
I realized a little information

00:18:43.490 --> 00:18:45.030
about the outside
world, they really

00:18:45.030 --> 00:18:47.130
soaked it up, like a sponge.

00:18:47.130 --> 00:18:49.980
So all of them
knew that there was

00:18:49.980 --> 00:18:53.760
this phenomenon outside that
they had no idea about called

00:18:53.760 --> 00:18:54.960
"Harry Potter."

00:18:54.960 --> 00:18:57.762
The things they knew was
"Harry Potter," JK Rowling,

00:18:57.762 --> 00:18:58.470
and what is that?

00:18:58.470 --> 00:18:59.469
The sports that they do.

00:18:59.469 --> 00:19:00.510
Kiddich or something?

00:19:00.510 --> 00:19:00.850
INTERVIEWER: Quidditch, yeah.

00:19:00.850 --> 00:19:01.600
SUKI KIM: Quidditch.

00:19:01.600 --> 00:19:02.100
Yeah.

00:19:02.100 --> 00:19:04.610
Quidditch, and then Harry,
and Ron, and Hermione.

00:19:04.610 --> 00:19:06.026
But they would ask
me things like,

00:19:06.026 --> 00:19:07.570
so is Quidditch really fun?

00:19:07.570 --> 00:19:09.460
And I would be like,
no, I don't play that.

00:19:09.460 --> 00:19:13.430
[CHUCKLES] So they were
really keen on this.

00:19:13.430 --> 00:19:16.230
And then by chance I found
out one of my colleagues

00:19:16.230 --> 00:19:18.870
had-- younger
colleagues, actually,

00:19:18.870 --> 00:19:23.320
from England had one of
the Harry Potter movies

00:19:23.320 --> 00:19:25.680
on her, like a DVD.

00:19:25.680 --> 00:19:30.250
So then I applied to teach
that to the counterparts

00:19:30.250 --> 00:19:32.260
because I said it's
mentioned in the textbooks.

00:19:32.260 --> 00:19:34.560
In order to finish my
lesson, it's important.

00:19:34.560 --> 00:19:37.260
It's detrimental to
my lesson that they

00:19:37.260 --> 00:19:39.270
understand what it is.

00:19:39.270 --> 00:19:41.669
And then it was actually
miraculously approved,

00:19:41.669 --> 00:19:42.710
which I couldn't believe.

00:19:42.710 --> 00:19:44.760
So the words just went
around the campus.

00:19:44.760 --> 00:19:46.440
They all were so excited.

00:19:46.440 --> 00:19:48.040
All day, I would get
like-- every day,

00:19:48.040 --> 00:19:49.670
it's like, so when
are we watching

00:19:49.670 --> 00:19:52.430
Harry and Hermione and Ron?

00:19:52.430 --> 00:19:57.350
And then my colleagues,
the Evangelical fundamental

00:19:57.350 --> 00:20:00.500
Christian group-- because there
were degrees in that group.

00:20:00.500 --> 00:20:03.630
Some were so much more
Orthodox than others.

00:20:03.630 --> 00:20:06.430
So more senior ones
actually came to me

00:20:06.430 --> 00:20:08.040
and said this is unacceptable.

00:20:08.040 --> 00:20:09.320
It's not going to happen.

00:20:09.320 --> 00:20:13.320
Because they said they were
now aiming for "Narnia."

00:20:13.320 --> 00:20:15.350
And "Narnia"--
I've never seen it,

00:20:15.350 --> 00:20:18.300
but "Narnia" has a very
religious tone to it,

00:20:18.300 --> 00:20:19.530
overtone to it.

00:20:19.530 --> 00:20:22.720
So they absolutely
forbade me, and they

00:20:22.720 --> 00:20:25.810
applied to teach
"Narnia," which then

00:20:25.810 --> 00:20:29.150
got rejected by the North
Korean counterparts.

00:20:29.150 --> 00:20:31.470
So it was suddenly a
battle between "Narnia"

00:20:31.470 --> 00:20:33.430
and "Harry Potter."

00:20:33.430 --> 00:20:40.805
And "Narnia," once it got
rejected, I was given a choice.

00:20:40.805 --> 00:20:45.200
And the Orthodox group, they
really felt that it was filth.

00:20:45.200 --> 00:20:49.160
So I had these crying and crying
moment just arguing with them.

00:20:49.160 --> 00:20:52.270
Because I was like, I don't
think Harry Potter is evil.

00:20:52.270 --> 00:20:54.590
And they were like, it's filth.

00:20:57.120 --> 00:20:59.340
And literally my
heart broke, I think,

00:20:59.340 --> 00:21:01.030
because it was so censored.

00:21:01.030 --> 00:21:03.620
My kids, they couldn't
have one or the other,

00:21:03.620 --> 00:21:05.520
because it was
complete censorship.

00:21:05.520 --> 00:21:07.470
They were just not
allowed this information.

00:21:07.470 --> 00:21:12.755
And I was given a choice to
show either one or the other.

00:21:12.755 --> 00:21:14.790
I taught two groups.

00:21:14.790 --> 00:21:18.812
Out of 270 young men, 50
were in my direct charge.

00:21:18.812 --> 00:21:21.270
So these are the kids that were
like my babies, 50 of them.

00:21:21.270 --> 00:21:23.080
And there were two
groups of them.

00:21:23.080 --> 00:21:28.640
And my colleagues, the
fundamentals Evangelicals said,

00:21:28.640 --> 00:21:29.870
choose one group.

00:21:29.870 --> 00:21:31.490
Then you can show it.

00:21:31.490 --> 00:21:37.650
So I was just really-- it was
a horrible choice to make,

00:21:37.650 --> 00:21:41.020
because I have to choose
one group of boys.

00:21:41.020 --> 00:21:43.290
And I did battle
with that decision,

00:21:43.290 --> 00:21:47.120
because I thought, how can I
break their hearts like that?

00:21:47.120 --> 00:21:49.280
Because they were
so disappointed.

00:21:49.280 --> 00:21:53.850
And I thought, you know, better
show it to one group than none.

00:21:53.850 --> 00:21:57.960
That was a choice that had to be
made, like a "Sophie's Choice."

00:21:57.960 --> 00:22:00.400
But they did see it.

00:22:00.400 --> 00:22:03.180
They marveled at watching it.

00:22:03.180 --> 00:22:05.604
And I thought they would
talk about things like the--

00:22:05.604 --> 00:22:08.145
because it was the third one,
which is really like, dramatic,

00:22:08.145 --> 00:22:09.540
the third installment.

00:22:09.540 --> 00:22:12.620
So I thought they would be
more fascinated by that.

00:22:12.620 --> 00:22:15.230
But in fact what was amazing
is because I had just been

00:22:15.230 --> 00:22:17.290
teaching essay writing to them.

00:22:17.290 --> 00:22:19.070
And essay writing,
by the way, was

00:22:19.070 --> 00:22:21.910
impossible to teach because
they didn't understand

00:22:21.910 --> 00:22:24.820
the whole concept of
coming on with an argument

00:22:24.820 --> 00:22:27.380
and proving it with evidence.

00:22:27.380 --> 00:22:28.820
That's what essays are about.

00:22:28.820 --> 00:22:31.780
And that was impossible there
because critical thinking

00:22:31.780 --> 00:22:33.450
is just not allowed.

00:22:33.450 --> 00:22:35.550
So we'd been battling with
essay writing so much.

00:22:35.550 --> 00:22:37.120
So when we watched
"Harry Potter,"

00:22:37.120 --> 00:22:39.700
there's a scene
where Hermione says,

00:22:39.700 --> 00:22:43.260
I have to write essays for
Professor Snape's class.

00:22:43.260 --> 00:22:47.540
And that's the moment
the boys talked about.

00:22:47.540 --> 00:22:51.270
They're like, Hermione has to
write an essay, too, like us.

00:22:51.270 --> 00:22:53.330
And I really thought, uh.

00:22:53.330 --> 00:22:55.840
This is what the
government is denying them.

00:22:55.840 --> 00:22:57.480
Basically it was the connection.

00:22:57.480 --> 00:23:01.260
It was the first time I
think they saw a Western film

00:23:01.260 --> 00:23:05.100
that they were-- they would only
get allowed things like "March

00:23:05.100 --> 00:23:11.510
of Penguins" and "Lion King,"
because those are like a nature

00:23:11.510 --> 00:23:13.280
film or the cartoon.

00:23:13.280 --> 00:23:16.680
This was a normal--
like people film.

00:23:16.680 --> 00:23:19.470
And that's what they latched
onto, was the connection,

00:23:19.470 --> 00:23:20.090
I thought.

00:23:20.090 --> 00:23:24.000
They really connected
with these kids like them.

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:27.380
And I thought, that's what their
government is denying them--

00:23:27.380 --> 00:23:31.170
complete blocking
them from relating

00:23:31.170 --> 00:23:32.650
to the rest of the world.

00:23:32.650 --> 00:23:34.055
It was a heartbreaking moment.

