00:23:55.230 --> 00:23:57.090
And that's referring
to their great leader,

00:23:57.090 --> 00:24:01.270
because great leader's
birthday is the Day of the Sun.

00:24:01.270 --> 00:24:03.390
So that's the original
great leader, Kim Jong-il,

00:24:03.390 --> 00:24:04.960
who died in 1994.

00:24:04.960 --> 00:24:07.980
And his entire
philosophy, Juche,

00:24:07.980 --> 00:24:10.570
is what North Korea is based on.

00:24:10.570 --> 00:24:12.753
And that's Kim Jong-il
flowers because all

00:24:12.753 --> 00:24:16.020
of the great leaders have
flowers invented for them.

00:24:16.020 --> 00:24:19.650
So this was Ministry
of Railways display

00:24:19.650 --> 00:24:23.440
of Kim Jong-il flowers to
celebrate Kim Jong-il's

00:24:23.440 --> 00:24:24.570
60th birthday.

00:24:24.570 --> 00:24:27.030
There were hundreds
of these displays.

00:24:27.030 --> 00:24:30.080
And I got taken to Kim Jong-il
flower exhibition, where

00:24:30.080 --> 00:24:33.020
I was given an explanation
about every single

00:24:33.020 --> 00:24:36.650
of those displays, which I think
might sound really fascinating.

00:24:36.650 --> 00:24:39.690
But I tell you, after
about like seven or eight,

00:24:39.690 --> 00:24:42.350
it's all the same because it's
all about the same flowers

00:24:42.350 --> 00:24:44.310
and the same theme.

00:24:44.310 --> 00:24:45.720
You see another one like that.

00:24:45.720 --> 00:24:48.240
I mean, there were
so many of these.

00:24:48.240 --> 00:24:49.970
These are the Workers'
Party leaders.

00:24:49.970 --> 00:24:53.120
Back in 2002, when
I went in, I had

00:24:53.120 --> 00:24:54.820
to do karaoke with those guys.

00:24:54.820 --> 00:24:55.320
[LAUGHTER]

00:24:55.320 --> 00:24:57.170
And that was a whole
other experience

00:24:57.170 --> 00:24:58.860
which I had to write about for
"New York Review of Books."

00:24:58.860 --> 00:24:59.675
INTERVIEWER: What did they sing?

00:24:59.675 --> 00:25:00.258
What did you--

00:25:00.258 --> 00:25:02.650
SUKI KIM: They were singing
obviously the only theme.

00:25:02.650 --> 00:25:04.430
What do you think
their songs were about?

00:25:04.430 --> 00:25:04.520
INTERVIEWER: Yeah.

00:25:04.520 --> 00:25:06.300
SUKI KIM: Obviously,
the great leader.

00:25:06.300 --> 00:25:08.240
I, actually-- the
only song allowed.

00:25:08.240 --> 00:25:10.530
I couldn't sing any
American songs, obviously,

00:25:10.530 --> 00:25:12.450
no English songs.

00:25:12.450 --> 00:25:14.040
I don't know any
North Korean songs.

00:25:14.040 --> 00:25:15.520
I could, but that
would have just

00:25:15.520 --> 00:25:18.180
seemed weird, for
me to suddenly start

00:25:18.180 --> 00:25:19.785
singing North Korean songs.

00:25:19.785 --> 00:25:21.900
But the only South
Korean song allowed

00:25:21.900 --> 00:25:25.500
was actually a protest song
against the dictator regime

00:25:25.500 --> 00:25:27.216
back in 1970s.

00:25:27.216 --> 00:25:29.090
And I thought that was
also very fascinating,

00:25:29.090 --> 00:25:31.460
songs that was actually
about a different time.

00:25:31.460 --> 00:25:34.620
In South Korea, which also had
a dictatorship back in 1970s

00:25:34.620 --> 00:25:37.640
against the government,
youth protest song,

00:25:37.640 --> 00:25:40.410
now that was used for
propaganda in North Korea

00:25:40.410 --> 00:25:43.750
later on, which I
thought was fascinating.

00:25:43.750 --> 00:25:45.484
Every mountain you get taken to.

00:25:45.484 --> 00:25:47.150
Well, I only got taken
to two mountains,

00:25:47.150 --> 00:25:48.780
but they're the most
famous mountains.

00:25:48.780 --> 00:25:51.390
And I think this is the case
with the rest of the mountains

00:25:51.390 --> 00:25:52.390
there.

00:25:52.390 --> 00:25:57.300
Every surface has those Kim
Jong-il stuff carved directly

00:25:57.300 --> 00:25:59.210
on the surface of the mountain.

00:25:59.210 --> 00:26:02.810
I think in Kumgangsan, which
is South Korea's-- I mean,

00:26:02.810 --> 00:26:07.240
the entire Korean peninsula's
most famous mountain has 4,000

00:26:07.240 --> 00:26:10.880
such carvings all
across the surface.

00:26:10.880 --> 00:26:13.470
So even the nature belongs
to the great leader.

00:26:13.470 --> 00:26:16.075
And generally it's saying things
like the great hero, our Kim

00:26:16.075 --> 00:26:17.300
Jong-il, and stuff like that.

00:26:17.300 --> 00:26:20.500
I mean, it's not really that
complicated what it says.

00:26:20.500 --> 00:26:22.740
So that's my kids.

00:26:22.740 --> 00:26:24.110
I think they're taking an exam.

00:26:24.110 --> 00:26:26.090
That's like a typical classroom.

00:26:26.090 --> 00:26:29.700
Yeah, so there
was like a lesson.

00:26:29.700 --> 00:26:33.390
That's where the great leaders--
now there are two of them--

00:26:33.390 --> 00:26:34.990
that are embalmed.

00:26:34.990 --> 00:26:38.700
So you go in there, and
you have to bow to him,

00:26:38.700 --> 00:26:41.700
and he's basically
lying there embalmed.

00:26:41.700 --> 00:26:45.020
And it's very, very
cold inside, obviously,

00:26:45.020 --> 00:26:48.030
because there's a
dead body in there.

00:26:48.030 --> 00:26:50.120
That's them watching
"Harry Potter" in my class.

00:26:50.120 --> 00:26:53.390
And you can only show, project
a movie very small there,

00:26:53.390 --> 00:26:54.060
I realized.

00:26:54.060 --> 00:26:57.470
Because there's no
blank space anywhere.

00:26:57.470 --> 00:26:59.910
And so those are Kim
Jong-il Kim Il-sung

00:26:59.910 --> 00:27:03.050
sayings, whatever they
said, which often like,

00:27:03.050 --> 00:27:04.460
our country's the greatest.

00:27:04.460 --> 00:27:05.710
It's all stuff like that.

00:27:05.710 --> 00:27:07.730
It's not also that complicated.

00:27:07.730 --> 00:27:11.690
So in every room, there's
those kind of fame and sayings

00:27:11.690 --> 00:27:14.750
by great leaders or
they're portraits.

00:27:14.750 --> 00:27:16.840
And you cannot move them.

00:27:16.840 --> 00:27:19.691
So if you can't move them,
there is no full blank space

00:27:19.691 --> 00:27:20.190
anywhere.

00:27:20.190 --> 00:27:22.590
So you have to just
show it half the size

00:27:22.590 --> 00:27:25.839
that you either can
watch at a big movie.

00:27:25.839 --> 00:27:27.130
So, I mean, we saw that before.

00:27:27.130 --> 00:27:31.840
But that walkway, I realized,
as I spent time there,

00:27:31.840 --> 00:27:34.890
made sure that there was
no privacy because you

00:27:34.890 --> 00:27:36.210
are seen everywhere.

00:27:36.210 --> 00:27:38.460
There are windows on
either side of that.

00:27:38.460 --> 00:27:42.370
So wherever you
are, you are seen.

00:27:42.370 --> 00:27:47.060
So that's my kids, a set of my
kids doing great leader duty.

00:27:47.060 --> 00:27:49.330
So there was a
building on campus

00:27:49.330 --> 00:27:53.195
that was basically a great
leader, Kim Jong-il-ism study

00:27:53.195 --> 00:27:54.290
hall.

00:27:54.290 --> 00:27:57.000
So that's where you go and study
the study of the great leader,

00:27:57.000 --> 00:28:00.670
and they went there every day
to learn great leader studies.

00:28:00.670 --> 00:28:04.980
And six students took
turns to guard it 24/7.

00:28:04.980 --> 00:28:07.510
So even if it's like
minus 40 degrees,

00:28:07.510 --> 00:28:10.182
you stand outside and
guard the building.

00:28:10.182 --> 00:28:11.140
It's an empty building.

00:28:11.140 --> 00:28:16.000
And they put on the--
basically the party uniform

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:19.940
in order to guard the building,
because it's a holy duty.

00:28:19.940 --> 00:28:24.050
So actually, my last day
there, Kim Jong-il died.

00:28:24.050 --> 00:28:25.730
And that was a coincidence.

00:28:25.730 --> 00:28:27.890
So I witnessed
the whole reaction

00:28:27.890 --> 00:28:29.240
to Kim Jong-il's death.

00:28:29.240 --> 00:28:34.050
And that's their only
newspaper announcing

00:28:34.050 --> 00:28:37.420
the death of Kim Jong-il,
which I ended up actually

00:28:37.420 --> 00:28:38.675
getting a copy of.

00:28:38.675 --> 00:28:40.050
INTERVIEWER: As
you were leaving.

00:28:40.050 --> 00:28:42.340
SUKI KIM: As I
was leaving, yeah.

00:28:42.340 --> 00:28:44.960
INTERVIEWER: Any questions?

00:28:44.960 --> 00:28:46.960
As you move to the mic,
I will ask one question.

00:28:46.960 --> 00:28:49.590
Do you think that it's a
good thing or a bad thing

00:28:49.590 --> 00:28:51.707
that tourism to North
Korea is increasing?

00:28:51.707 --> 00:28:53.290
Obviously that's
giving money to the--

00:28:53.290 --> 00:28:53.800
SUKI KIM: Tourists.

00:28:53.800 --> 00:28:54.925
INTERVIEWER: Tourism, Yeah.

00:28:58.170 --> 00:29:01.450
SUKI KIM: I'm against
it, personally.

00:29:01.450 --> 00:29:03.190
That's my personal opinion.

00:29:03.190 --> 00:29:07.890
I think different engagement
methods are probably necessary.

00:29:07.890 --> 00:29:09.520
But tours?

00:29:09.520 --> 00:29:11.300
I don't know what
there is to tour about.

00:29:11.300 --> 00:29:15.930
I don't know about-- they called
them torture porn or something.

00:29:15.930 --> 00:29:21.230
I think there's a term for that,
voyeurism with poverty tours.

00:29:21.230 --> 00:29:24.150
And it's a gulag
pretending to be a nation.

00:29:24.150 --> 00:29:28.960
And that money the tourists
spend, it might seem curious.

00:29:28.960 --> 00:29:32.430
But it's not that curious,
because you get taken

00:29:32.430 --> 00:29:35.920
to the exact four, five sites.

00:29:35.920 --> 00:29:38.030
And it's just not that funny.

00:29:38.030 --> 00:29:41.520
North Korea is literally a
gulag pretending to be a nation.

00:29:41.520 --> 00:29:45.980
And every penny you spend there
will go directly to the regime

00:29:45.980 --> 00:29:49.650
to suppress and torture
and execute their people.

00:29:49.650 --> 00:29:53.930
So I do think actually that
tourist money is not money.

00:29:53.930 --> 00:29:56.506
It's bolstering the regime.

00:29:56.506 --> 00:29:58.710
INTERVIEWER: OK.

00:29:58.710 --> 00:30:01.330
AUDIENCE: I'm really
curious about storytelling.

00:30:01.330 --> 00:30:03.570
You mentioned that you showed
"Harry Potter" to them.

00:30:03.570 --> 00:30:05.445
And I'm curious about
like-- because you only

00:30:05.445 --> 00:30:06.430
showed it to one class.

00:30:06.430 --> 00:30:09.530
And I'm wondering, was it
retold to the other class?

00:30:09.530 --> 00:30:13.120
And how did that story
kind of propagate, and how

00:30:13.120 --> 00:30:16.760
does storytelling generally
work within that kind

00:30:16.760 --> 00:30:18.445
of environment?

00:30:18.445 --> 00:30:19.570
SUKI KIM: What do you mean?

00:30:19.570 --> 00:30:21.970
The storytelling of
whatever happens?

00:30:21.970 --> 00:30:23.650
I mean, it's an
important method there.

00:30:23.650 --> 00:30:27.295
One of the things actually
they did to amuse themselves,

00:30:27.295 --> 00:30:30.370
which seems, really,
you know, they're kind

00:30:30.370 --> 00:30:32.130
of too old for it-- 19, 20.

00:30:32.130 --> 00:30:34.370
But they did tell stories
to amuse themselves.

00:30:34.370 --> 00:30:35.590
They did nothing else.

00:30:35.590 --> 00:30:38.280
So they told me in
evenings, they-- there

00:30:38.280 --> 00:30:39.910
was a little free
time they gather

00:30:39.910 --> 00:30:43.440
to watch their television, which
is all about the great leader.

00:30:43.440 --> 00:30:46.600
So I think a lot of
times with the TV on,

00:30:46.600 --> 00:30:48.410
they did little games and stuff.

00:30:48.410 --> 00:30:51.470
But they said they
would do stories.

00:30:51.470 --> 00:30:53.536
They would make like
one is playing a boy.

00:30:53.536 --> 00:30:54.660
Like almost like a theater.

00:30:54.660 --> 00:30:58.430
But they would tell stories,
like little made-up theater

00:30:58.430 --> 00:31:00.180
to entertain themselves.

00:31:00.180 --> 00:31:04.526
I mean, it seems so not
2015 kind of an amusement,

00:31:04.526 --> 00:31:05.400
but they did do that.

00:31:05.400 --> 00:31:07.340
So it is, actually,
I think a way they

00:31:07.340 --> 00:31:08.950
do entertain themselves there.

00:31:13.109 --> 00:31:13.650
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:31:13.650 --> 00:31:14.470
Fascinating stuff.

00:31:14.470 --> 00:31:15.970
Thanks so much.

00:31:15.970 --> 00:31:18.310
I wondered just a bit
more about sort of whether

00:31:18.310 --> 00:31:21.100
or not your sense of whether
or not people actually

00:31:21.100 --> 00:31:22.240
question anything.

00:31:22.240 --> 00:31:23.930
Because you talked
about the fact

00:31:23.930 --> 00:31:26.360
that they are totally isolated.

00:31:26.360 --> 00:31:28.390
That isn't like some
fake they just don't

00:31:28.390 --> 00:31:29.830
know what's going on outside.

00:31:29.830 --> 00:31:32.288
But do you get any sense of
that they're actually beginning

00:31:32.288 --> 00:31:34.550
to question what's going on?

00:31:34.550 --> 00:31:36.260
Like what are they looking for?

00:31:36.260 --> 00:31:38.770
For example, when
they couldn't watch

00:31:38.770 --> 00:31:42.130
"Harry Potter," that class,
the authorities had said no.

00:31:42.130 --> 00:31:44.090
Is that something that
actually upset them

00:31:44.090 --> 00:31:45.610
and made them think about it?

00:31:45.610 --> 00:31:50.174
Or did they just have total
obedience to their leadership?

00:31:50.174 --> 00:31:51.090
SUKI KIM: It is there.

00:31:51.090 --> 00:31:55.290
Of course it's there, the
doubt against the regime.

00:31:55.290 --> 00:32:00.180
But it is so squashed
that-- you know,

00:32:00.180 --> 00:32:03.071
there are different
levels of that.

00:32:03.071 --> 00:32:05.320
Number one is actually
something that we didn't finish

00:32:05.320 --> 00:32:08.680
talking about, which is lies.

00:32:08.680 --> 00:32:11.030
My students lied all the time.

00:32:11.030 --> 00:32:13.230
There were different
levels of lies.

00:32:13.230 --> 00:32:15.230
One, they lied because
they were always

00:32:15.230 --> 00:32:17.795
fearful of-- like the
guard duty, for example.

00:32:17.795 --> 00:32:19.170
They would do
those guard duties,

00:32:19.170 --> 00:32:20.940
and they would say
they didn't do it,

00:32:20.940 --> 00:32:22.230
although I saw them do it.

00:32:22.230 --> 00:32:25.310
So it was such a lie
that made no sense.

00:32:25.310 --> 00:32:29.710
Or they would say like, I
cloned a rabbit in fifth grade.

00:32:29.710 --> 00:32:31.890
And, you know,
just nonsense lies.

00:32:31.890 --> 00:32:35.750
But I think they were
regurgitating those lies.

00:32:35.750 --> 00:32:37.450
Or sometimes they
lied out of habit.

00:32:37.450 --> 00:32:40.720
So this whole lying culture
does make it very difficult

00:32:40.720 --> 00:32:42.550
to see what's really going on.

00:32:42.550 --> 00:32:44.700
And that's a part of the
whole propaganda thing.

00:32:44.700 --> 00:32:48.250
And you constantly have to
pretend to do something else.

00:32:48.250 --> 00:32:50.040
It creates a shield,
and you can't really

00:32:50.040 --> 00:32:51.300
see what's going on.

00:32:51.300 --> 00:32:54.520
So that lying culture made
that really difficult.

00:32:54.520 --> 00:32:57.580
But I think the more and
more I was there, I did

00:32:57.580 --> 00:33:00.597
think there were
slight questions why.

00:33:00.597 --> 00:33:01.680
Because they would ask me.

00:33:01.680 --> 00:33:04.460
Of course they could see
that I'm traveling freely.

00:33:04.460 --> 00:33:05.460
And they're not.

00:33:05.460 --> 00:33:06.835
They're not even
allowed to leave

00:33:06.835 --> 00:33:08.710
their-- none of
those kids had ever

00:33:08.710 --> 00:33:10.750
been to any of those mountains.

00:33:10.750 --> 00:33:11.660
And these are elite.

00:33:11.660 --> 00:33:13.940
They've never been to
their country's most famous

00:33:13.940 --> 00:33:15.770
mountains, because
they're not allowed.

00:33:15.770 --> 00:33:17.530
So I think they
did question that.

00:33:17.530 --> 00:33:20.410
But the questions
that-- I mean, I

00:33:20.410 --> 00:33:22.675
think this is probably our
best way to think about it.

00:33:22.675 --> 00:33:24.174
I think two ways
is probably easiest

00:33:24.174 --> 00:33:26.760
to think about that question,
which gets asked most often.

00:33:26.760 --> 00:33:28.230
How much do they really know?

00:33:28.230 --> 00:33:31.220
I think humanity is not
that different anywhere.

00:33:31.220 --> 00:33:33.920
But this is all they've
known and born into.

00:33:33.920 --> 00:33:39.059
So even though they might
question for a second,

00:33:39.059 --> 00:33:41.100
within that context, I
think if you think of them

00:33:41.100 --> 00:33:44.350
as the most abused household.

00:33:44.350 --> 00:33:48.760
So if you've basically been
born and bred in endless abuse--

00:33:48.760 --> 00:33:50.980
physically, and
emotionally, psychologically

00:33:50.980 --> 00:33:52.830
beaten every single
day-- that I think

00:33:52.830 --> 00:33:56.240
it is really hard to
fathom what else is there.

00:33:56.240 --> 00:33:57.520
So there's that level.

00:33:57.520 --> 00:34:00.754
But I think also the
control that they have,

00:34:00.754 --> 00:34:03.170
making sure you don't move,
physically, because you're not

00:34:03.170 --> 00:34:04.480
allowed to move anywhere.

00:34:04.480 --> 00:34:07.497
Make sure you don't share any
information, because you're not

00:34:07.497 --> 00:34:08.420
allowed.

00:34:08.420 --> 00:34:11.909
And I think that just binds you.

00:34:11.909 --> 00:34:12.860
You become helpless.

00:34:12.860 --> 00:34:14.690
There's not much you can do.

00:34:14.690 --> 00:34:17.245
And I think also the punishment
is so great when there's

00:34:17.245 --> 00:34:19.460
a gulag, and there's
public execution,

00:34:19.460 --> 00:34:21.500
and also you report
on each other.

00:34:21.500 --> 00:34:23.320
So I think that all
those doubts-- I

00:34:23.320 --> 00:34:25.650
did see little inklings of it.

00:34:25.650 --> 00:34:28.000
But it gets squashed so quickly.

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:31.610
I mean, it's just like there's
not a-- it's like so rapid.

00:34:31.610 --> 00:34:34.070
It's a moment of a
flicker, and it's gone.

00:34:34.070 --> 00:34:36.360
And I think it's
because punishment is--

00:34:36.360 --> 00:34:40.580
and so in answer to that,
I think it's like us.

00:34:40.580 --> 00:34:42.340
It's not that different
on some level,

00:34:42.340 --> 00:34:44.679
but it's so
tremendously different.

00:34:44.679 --> 00:34:47.659
And the punishment is
beyond what we can fathom.

00:34:47.659 --> 00:34:50.409
And if you are
living in a gulag,

00:34:50.409 --> 00:34:53.199
and one thing you say
wrong would get you

00:34:53.199 --> 00:34:57.340
and your family and
everyone you know killed,

00:34:57.340 --> 00:35:01.333
then you would probably not
express more than a second.

00:35:01.333 --> 00:35:03.970
AUDIENCE: Just another
super quick question,

00:35:03.970 --> 00:35:06.050
which may just be a yes or no.

00:35:06.050 --> 00:35:08.890
Do you think this regime
will fall in our lifetime?

00:35:11.620 --> 00:35:14.000
SUKI KIM: I mean, the world
has been questioning that.

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:17.430
So I don't-- I mean, I cannot--
I don't think that I say that

00:35:17.430 --> 00:35:21.480
authoritatively, but having
studied this topic as long as I

00:35:21.480 --> 00:35:24.100
could stand it and
having been there,

00:35:24.100 --> 00:35:25.710
I've also talked to
all the defectors,

00:35:25.710 --> 00:35:27.501
traveled to all of the
surrounding regions.

00:35:27.501 --> 00:35:30.022
I mean, I've just been
following it for over a decade.

00:35:30.022 --> 00:35:34.760
And I just feel like
that's up to us.

00:35:34.760 --> 00:35:38.010
I think I did come to a
conclusion by living in there.

00:35:38.010 --> 00:35:40.820
I don't know if it
could come from inside.

00:35:40.820 --> 00:35:43.680
You might see little
flickers, but that flicker

00:35:43.680 --> 00:35:44.820
gets squashed so quickly.

00:35:44.820 --> 00:35:48.080
I think whoever talks about
North Korea's spring compared

00:35:48.080 --> 00:35:50.090
to Arab spring or
compared to Cuba

00:35:50.090 --> 00:35:53.470
or compared to East Germany,
West Germany, all of that,

00:35:53.470 --> 00:35:56.170
I personally think that's
nonsense because we've never

00:35:56.170 --> 00:35:57.300
seen anything like this.

00:35:57.300 --> 00:36:00.780
A gulag concentration camp
in existence for 70 years?

00:36:00.780 --> 00:36:03.040
That's a different
animal altogether.

00:36:03.040 --> 00:36:05.970
This goes back to why
backpacking, touring into North

00:36:05.970 --> 00:36:08.690
Korea, I'm against it.

00:36:08.690 --> 00:36:11.860
So I don't know if it
could fall on its own.

00:36:11.860 --> 00:36:14.620
But I do think-- I
find it a little-- I

00:36:14.620 --> 00:36:17.050
mean, one of the reasons
for writing this book,

00:36:17.050 --> 00:36:20.140
and it is a bit nutty thing
to do to go in there, I think,

00:36:20.140 --> 00:36:20.780
undercover.

00:36:20.780 --> 00:36:24.230
But I think I just find
it morally unacceptable

00:36:24.230 --> 00:36:29.870
that world is there, and
the rest of us are here.

00:36:29.870 --> 00:36:32.700
There's something really
deeply disturbing about

00:36:32.700 --> 00:36:37.060
that, I think just
humanity in general,

00:36:37.060 --> 00:36:39.610
because I think it's horrific.

00:36:39.610 --> 00:36:40.421
So I don't know.

00:36:40.421 --> 00:36:42.170
I don't think they can
do it on their own,

00:36:42.170 --> 00:36:45.401
but I think the world can
maybe make that happen.

00:36:45.401 --> 00:36:47.150
I think the first step
is caring about it,

00:36:47.150 --> 00:36:49.691
caring about the issue, and then
maybe something will change.

00:36:49.691 --> 00:36:50.260
I don't know.

00:36:50.260 --> 00:36:52.340
But I think it's up to us.

00:36:52.340 --> 00:36:55.569
INTERVIEWER: Thanks a lot.

00:36:55.569 --> 00:36:56.110
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:36:56.110 --> 00:36:57.832
Thanks for being here today.

00:36:57.832 --> 00:36:59.790
My question has to do
with academic curriculum.

00:36:59.790 --> 00:37:02.780
I wonder if you can expound
a bit about, if you know,

00:37:02.780 --> 00:37:05.240
what the average
14-year-old learns.

00:37:05.240 --> 00:37:08.240
And the reason I
ask is because it's

00:37:08.240 --> 00:37:11.010
been said that knowledge
is power, and all this.

00:37:11.010 --> 00:37:12.940
I think if it's a
subject like math, where

00:37:12.940 --> 00:37:15.730
it can be taught rotely,
and you learn the facts,

00:37:15.730 --> 00:37:19.945
and it never sort of expands
your mind into the world-- one

00:37:19.945 --> 00:37:20.570
interpretation.

00:37:20.570 --> 00:37:22.729
But something like
literature or economics,

00:37:22.729 --> 00:37:24.770
how can you learn those
subjects without thinking

00:37:24.770 --> 00:37:26.400
about the world?

00:37:26.400 --> 00:37:29.409
And is it done that way?

00:37:29.409 --> 00:37:31.450
SUKI KIM: I think that's
another-- because people

00:37:31.450 --> 00:37:34.030
do ask me about reunification.

00:37:34.030 --> 00:37:35.330
What do I think?

00:37:35.330 --> 00:37:38.220
And I think that goes back
to that education thing.

00:37:38.220 --> 00:37:40.020
Like where do we begin?

00:37:40.020 --> 00:37:42.690
Because what I
saw there was it's

00:37:42.690 --> 00:37:47.570
not possible to teach economics
and literature without bringing

00:37:47.570 --> 00:37:48.990
the world in there.

00:37:48.990 --> 00:37:52.690
So if they have the
basic information--

00:37:52.690 --> 00:37:53.550
they were so bright.

00:37:53.550 --> 00:37:55.610
I mean, they learned
English so quickly.

00:37:55.610 --> 00:37:57.290
They worked so hard.

00:37:57.290 --> 00:37:59.330
But their general
knowledge had a gap

00:37:59.330 --> 00:38:02.950
that I just could
not understand.

00:38:02.950 --> 00:38:08.330
They thought scientists changed
blood type A to B-- North

00:38:08.330 --> 00:38:10.280
Korean scientists, of course.

00:38:10.280 --> 00:38:14.170
So if you teach that to
students in a science class,

00:38:14.170 --> 00:38:19.930
or they learned basketball
makes them grow taller.

00:38:19.930 --> 00:38:24.260
So, I mean, it's basically
teaching nonsense.

00:38:24.260 --> 00:38:28.717
Because in order to teach
economics or science or any

00:38:28.717 --> 00:38:30.550
of these things-- how
can you teach computer

00:38:30.550 --> 00:38:33.220
without telling them about
Steve Jobs or Mark Zuckerberg

00:38:33.220 --> 00:38:35.250
or the internet or any of it?

00:38:35.250 --> 00:38:39.660
So I did not-- and literature,
out of the question.

00:38:39.660 --> 00:38:42.650
The only book they are
allowed to learn that is not

00:38:42.650 --> 00:38:46.450
North Korean was
"Disappeared with the Wind"--

00:38:46.450 --> 00:38:49.970
"Gone with the Wind," which
is about North and South

00:38:49.970 --> 00:38:54.530
civil war, where North wins.

00:38:54.530 --> 00:38:57.740
There's all reasons why only
that information is allowed.

00:38:57.740 --> 00:39:01.010
So, I mean, what
literature do they know?

00:39:01.010 --> 00:39:02.910
Only the great
leader's literature.

00:39:02.910 --> 00:39:06.110
So I don't think that education
as we know it exists there.

00:39:06.110 --> 00:39:09.872
Because their system is
designed in order to uphold

00:39:09.872 --> 00:39:11.080
the myth of the great leader.

00:39:11.080 --> 00:39:13.100
In order to uphold
that, they need

00:39:13.100 --> 00:39:14.960
to make their students dumb.

00:39:14.960 --> 00:39:17.530
And that was really
difficult to stomach,

00:39:17.530 --> 00:39:21.760
because they were so bright,
they were so sweet, so lovely.

00:39:21.760 --> 00:39:24.303
They just did not
know much of anything.

00:39:24.303 --> 00:39:25.136
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:39:28.870 --> 00:39:29.620
AUDIENCE: Hi Suki.

00:39:29.620 --> 00:39:30.770
My name is Arvin.

00:39:30.770 --> 00:39:35.180
I had a quick question about
the "Harry Potter" movie again.

00:39:35.180 --> 00:39:38.960
I was wondering, was parts
of the movie censored?

00:39:38.960 --> 00:39:41.210
Because I know it's
a fictional movie,

00:39:41.210 --> 00:39:43.990
so I guess that's why it
was allowed, because it kind

00:39:43.990 --> 00:39:45.340
of shows a fictional world.

00:39:45.340 --> 00:39:47.460
But the beginning
of the movie shows

00:39:47.460 --> 00:39:49.790
parts of London, people
taking the train,

00:39:49.790 --> 00:39:53.270
and they're living in houses
and interacting with each other.

00:39:53.270 --> 00:39:54.660
I was wondering,
were those parts

00:39:54.660 --> 00:39:56.229
of the movie
completely censored?

00:39:56.229 --> 00:39:56.770
SUKI KIM: No.

00:39:56.770 --> 00:40:00.080
Amazingly, the North Korean
staff just let it happen.

00:40:00.080 --> 00:40:02.400
Because I think it was
mentioned in the textbook.

00:40:02.400 --> 00:40:05.180
So they were just kind of
bureaucrats with that one--

00:40:05.180 --> 00:40:06.750
luckily passed it.

00:40:06.750 --> 00:40:08.400
And they could have
easily said no.

00:40:08.400 --> 00:40:11.470
But I think some of it, I
was thinking at the time--

00:40:11.470 --> 00:40:14.050
because it's also
a little mythical.

00:40:14.050 --> 00:40:16.760
It's not kind of
real London, is it?

00:40:16.760 --> 00:40:17.500
Obviously not.

00:40:17.500 --> 00:40:19.050
It's Harry Potter's London.

00:40:19.050 --> 00:40:23.540
So I think that's why it was
kind of magic thing made it

00:40:23.540 --> 00:40:29.510
better than like a normal
today's London visuals, which

00:40:29.510 --> 00:40:31.766
they wouldn't have wanted.

00:40:31.766 --> 00:40:33.030
AUDIENCE: One other question.

00:40:33.030 --> 00:40:35.276
Was the movie screened
in English or--

00:40:35.276 --> 00:40:37.400
SUKI KIM: Yeah, because
they were learning English.

00:40:37.400 --> 00:40:39.420
So that was a part
of an English lesson.

00:40:39.420 --> 00:40:41.503
AUDIENCE: And I saw on the
picture there was text.

00:40:41.503 --> 00:40:43.870
Was that North Korean text
so they could understand,

00:40:43.870 --> 00:40:45.677
or were they speaking
fluent English?

00:40:45.677 --> 00:40:47.010
SUKI KIM: What do you mean text?

00:40:47.010 --> 00:40:47.590
There was--

00:40:47.590 --> 00:40:50.285
AUDIENCE: I think on the
picture there was subtitles.

00:40:50.285 --> 00:40:52.160
SUKI KIM: The pictures
didn't have subtitles.

00:40:52.160 --> 00:40:55.470
I think it was my
writing to explain maybe

00:40:55.470 --> 00:40:56.430
in Korean or something.

00:40:56.430 --> 00:40:57.870
No, there was no subtitle.

00:40:57.870 --> 00:40:59.570
No, they understood the movie.

00:40:59.570 --> 00:41:01.900
Their English was very good.

00:41:01.900 --> 00:41:03.110
AUDIENCE: And last question.

00:41:03.110 --> 00:41:04.651
It might be a more
personal question.

00:41:04.651 --> 00:41:09.760
I was wondering, like coming
back to the Western world

00:41:09.760 --> 00:41:12.705
and writing this book and
speaking about your experience,

00:41:12.705 --> 00:41:17.840
do you ever feel that you're
threatened or exposed?

00:41:17.840 --> 00:41:18.340
Like--

00:41:18.340 --> 00:41:18.740
SUKI KIM: Me?

00:41:18.740 --> 00:41:19.365
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:41:19.365 --> 00:41:22.160
SUKI KIM: Well, that was always
a part of the whole thing.

00:41:22.160 --> 00:41:26.530
I think obviously being
there was the worst of it.

00:41:26.530 --> 00:41:31.640
Consequences were frightening.

00:41:31.640 --> 00:41:37.130
So when one side started
following this topic

00:41:37.130 --> 00:41:41.660
and deciding to write a
book, that scary part of it,

00:41:41.660 --> 00:41:43.970
which I was scared, every
single day, of being there.

00:41:43.970 --> 00:41:46.450
And sometime after when
the book was coming out,

00:41:46.450 --> 00:41:47.685
I was getting threats.

00:41:47.685 --> 00:41:48.761
So it was scary.

00:41:48.761 --> 00:41:51.260
AUDIENCE: Where you getting
like emails from the government?

00:41:51.260 --> 00:41:54.530
SUKI KIM: I was getting emails
from the head of that school,

00:41:54.530 --> 00:41:59.220
who are working with the regime
to absolutely stop publication,

00:41:59.220 --> 00:42:00.840
send the manuscript to them.

00:42:00.840 --> 00:42:03.967
And it was threatening.

00:42:03.967 --> 00:42:04.800
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:42:04.800 --> 00:42:05.811
SUKI KIM: Thanks.

00:42:05.811 --> 00:42:08.220
INTERVIEWER: Do you regret
that you can't go back?

00:42:08.220 --> 00:42:09.160
SUKI KIM: Oh, I'm
not going back, no.

00:42:09.160 --> 00:42:10.090
INTERVIEWER: No,
but did you regret

00:42:10.090 --> 00:42:11.430
that you can't go back again?

00:42:11.430 --> 00:42:14.890
SUKI KIM: No, because I
feel like I poured myself

00:42:14.890 --> 00:42:17.280
into-- this whole
project took, I think,

00:42:17.280 --> 00:42:18.650
12 years from the beginning.

00:42:18.650 --> 00:42:19.358
INTERVIEWER: Wow.

00:42:19.358 --> 00:42:23.410
SUKI KIM: And I threw
everything I know

00:42:23.410 --> 00:42:26.140
into this book on the topic.

00:42:26.140 --> 00:42:30.430
So there isn't really much
more I can say at the moment,

00:42:30.430 --> 00:42:31.570
I think.

00:42:31.570 --> 00:42:35.590
I got to understand it, I think,
as I possibly humanly could.

00:42:35.590 --> 00:42:38.360
So I think if I do go back,
maybe something would have

00:42:38.360 --> 00:42:40.180
changed in that
world, or something

00:42:40.180 --> 00:42:43.500
in different circumstances,
so I can find different truth.

00:42:43.500 --> 00:42:47.260
INTERVIEWER: We'll take--
oh-- these questions,

00:42:47.260 --> 00:42:48.510
but make them shorter.

00:42:48.510 --> 00:42:49.265
OK.

00:42:49.265 --> 00:42:50.640
AUDIENCE: My
question is actually

00:42:50.640 --> 00:42:51.340
related to fear as well.

00:42:51.340 --> 00:42:52.950
Because presumably,
those kids must

00:42:52.950 --> 00:42:58.180
live under such constant fear
all the time and distress.

00:42:58.180 --> 00:43:00.320
Did you see it
manifested in any way?

00:43:00.320 --> 00:43:01.490
SUKI KIM: Did I see what?

00:43:01.490 --> 00:43:02.510
AUDIENCE: Did you
see it manifested?

00:43:02.510 --> 00:43:03.424
How did it manifest?

00:43:03.424 --> 00:43:05.090
SUKI KIM: The fear,
how did it manifest.

00:43:05.090 --> 00:43:08.719
The fears manifested-- the
fears were every second.

00:43:08.719 --> 00:43:10.510
The fears-- you know,
I think it's amazing.

00:43:10.510 --> 00:43:12.680
Human beings, one of
the most primal feelings

00:43:12.680 --> 00:43:15.550
that we can sense is fear.

00:43:15.550 --> 00:43:18.030
And I felt that
so strongly there.

00:43:18.030 --> 00:43:20.240
So I mean, a very, very moment.

00:43:20.240 --> 00:43:21.220
It's in the book.

00:43:21.220 --> 00:43:23.590
When they say, what do
you sing when you all

00:43:23.590 --> 00:43:25.165
get together to
celebrate birthday,

00:43:25.165 --> 00:43:27.590
because that's what they
do, or do storytelling.

00:43:27.590 --> 00:43:31.240
And they said, you know,
songs about the great leader.

00:43:31.240 --> 00:43:33.820
And one time, one student
said rock and roll.

00:43:33.820 --> 00:43:36.990
And the whole table froze.

00:43:36.990 --> 00:43:39.510
And that moment
was absolute fear.

00:43:39.510 --> 00:43:41.840
Like my heart sank
when he said that.

00:43:41.840 --> 00:43:45.320
Because he just looked around
to see who else heard it,

00:43:45.320 --> 00:43:46.550
and I looked around.

00:43:46.550 --> 00:43:49.510
And I remember just my whole
body-- my feet felt cold.

00:43:49.510 --> 00:43:53.180
Because I realized that he could
be punished because of this.

00:43:53.180 --> 00:43:54.680
We all changed the
topic instantly.

00:43:54.680 --> 00:43:57.550
But it was moments like
that, something so tiny.

00:43:57.550 --> 00:43:59.959
But the fear there was palpable.

00:43:59.959 --> 00:44:00.750
You could touch it.

00:44:03.584 --> 00:44:04.375
AUDIENCE: Hi, Suki.

00:44:04.375 --> 00:44:06.820
Thank you for your
really fascinating talk.

00:44:06.820 --> 00:44:08.570
I just wanted to
ask you, have you

00:44:08.570 --> 00:44:10.200
been involved in any
political activism

00:44:10.200 --> 00:44:12.070
off the back of
all the attention

00:44:12.070 --> 00:44:13.720
that the book is getting?

00:44:13.720 --> 00:44:15.930
Because I can
imagine-- I mean, we

00:44:15.930 --> 00:44:18.550
talk about the Holocaust
and the Second World War

00:44:18.550 --> 00:44:19.989
constantly, even to this day.

00:44:19.989 --> 00:44:22.280
And like you mentioned, this
is even greater than that.

00:44:22.280 --> 00:44:24.260
It's been going on for 70 years.

00:44:24.260 --> 00:44:26.300
And we still talk
about the guilt

00:44:26.300 --> 00:44:32.820
about how come we didn't go into
help Poland, Netherlands, all

00:44:32.820 --> 00:44:34.610
the Second World War still.

00:44:34.610 --> 00:44:36.550
And this is on a
much bigger scale.

00:44:36.550 --> 00:44:38.510
So does the book affect
anything politically?

00:44:38.510 --> 00:44:44.200
Is there any move into
maybe the UN or the US

00:44:44.200 --> 00:44:46.800
or anyone going in there after--

00:44:46.800 --> 00:44:52.640
SUKI KIM: I think as my job,
I mean, the best I could do

00:44:52.640 --> 00:44:58.140
was vividly deliver that
world in the deepest

00:44:58.140 --> 00:45:02.470
way I know how to the world
so the world can feel.

00:45:02.470 --> 00:45:06.950
I always said the purpose
was to humanize North Korea.

00:45:06.950 --> 00:45:09.410
So through this book,
if people can actually

00:45:09.410 --> 00:45:12.200
feel humanly feelings
towards the people there,

00:45:12.200 --> 00:45:15.220
25 million people, who
have now become, sadly,

00:45:15.220 --> 00:45:18.760
butt of Kim Jong-il jokes,
which are really tiresome.

00:45:18.760 --> 00:45:21.970
And so I think that, as
a writer, that's the most

00:45:21.970 --> 00:45:22.550
I can do.

00:45:22.550 --> 00:45:24.930
And also bring
back-- another one

00:45:24.930 --> 00:45:27.910
that I-- you know, the
reason we have North Korea

00:45:27.910 --> 00:45:29.360
is because there
was a Korean War.

00:45:29.360 --> 00:45:33.410
And the truth about the Korean
War, which the world calls

00:45:33.410 --> 00:45:35.930
"forgotten war," and
this forgotten war,

00:45:35.930 --> 00:45:38.360
millions of people got
separated and died.

00:45:38.360 --> 00:45:40.450
And where it really
began has a lot

00:45:40.450 --> 00:45:43.970
to do with actually the
Second World War remapping

00:45:43.970 --> 00:45:45.780
of colonial powers,
starting with the UK,

00:45:45.780 --> 00:45:51.410
actually, and China
and ultimately

00:45:51.410 --> 00:45:54.840
the US and Soviet Union.

00:45:54.840 --> 00:45:58.930
And that remapping created
the division of two Koreas.

00:45:58.930 --> 00:46:00.620
It's never a civil war.

00:46:00.620 --> 00:46:02.950
And how it affected
that decision that

00:46:02.950 --> 00:46:05.840
began from the Cairo
Conference, where

00:46:05.840 --> 00:46:08.240
it began in 1943,
with remapping,

00:46:08.240 --> 00:46:11.840
and how it resulted in
the division of a country.

00:46:11.840 --> 00:46:14.970
And that ended up separating
millions of families

00:46:14.970 --> 00:46:17.820
and created today's North Korea.

00:46:17.820 --> 00:46:19.570
And I thought, you
know, all I can

00:46:19.570 --> 00:46:23.110
do is to relate that
in a readable way

00:46:23.110 --> 00:46:26.030
so that people begin
thinking about it

00:46:26.030 --> 00:46:30.320
and thinking a little
more deeply about why

00:46:30.320 --> 00:46:31.930
we have this tragedy today.

00:46:31.930 --> 00:46:34.640
And I don't think--
I mean, I don't know.

00:46:34.640 --> 00:46:37.390
Like, political
activism, I think

00:46:37.390 --> 00:46:39.320
that's for activists to do.

00:46:39.320 --> 00:46:42.010
As a writer, all I can
do is write the best book

00:46:42.010 --> 00:46:44.596
I know how on the topic.

00:46:44.596 --> 00:46:45.512
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:46:48.720 --> 00:46:50.700
AUDIENCE: Thank you
very much again.

00:46:50.700 --> 00:46:53.550
Given that your students can be
quite directly linked to you,

00:46:53.550 --> 00:46:57.360
even if you try to cover
things up in the book,

00:46:57.360 --> 00:46:59.112
it seems that there's
a risk for them.

00:46:59.112 --> 00:47:01.070
Do you know if there have
been any consequences

00:47:01.070 --> 00:47:01.820
for your students?

00:47:01.820 --> 00:47:03.800
SUKI KIM: The consequences
from this book

00:47:03.800 --> 00:47:07.180
was something that was
brought up from the beginning,

00:47:07.180 --> 00:47:07.950
right away.

00:47:07.950 --> 00:47:10.990
It was obviously the
foremost on my mind.

00:47:10.990 --> 00:47:12.700
People questioned a
lot the consequences

00:47:12.700 --> 00:47:14.950
for it, actually, the
Evangelical Christians

00:47:14.950 --> 00:47:17.320
who brought me in.

00:47:17.320 --> 00:47:20.700
I mean, clearly that group
works with the government.

00:47:20.700 --> 00:47:23.050
So it's not like the
fact they were missionary

00:47:23.050 --> 00:47:24.120
was ever a secret.

00:47:24.120 --> 00:47:25.071
I didn't out them.

00:47:25.071 --> 00:47:27.570
I'm sure it's unpleasant for
them to have the book come out,

00:47:27.570 --> 00:47:30.620
because it's made,
probably, things difficult.

00:47:30.620 --> 00:47:32.680
But, you know, the
book was worth it.

00:47:32.680 --> 00:47:34.430
But it was not going
to sabotage them

00:47:34.430 --> 00:47:37.340
in any way that has to do
with real consequences.

00:47:37.340 --> 00:47:41.140
I would think probably moneywise
it might have been hard

00:47:41.140 --> 00:47:43.240
for them on some level to
have to raise more money

00:47:43.240 --> 00:47:45.336
for the regime on some level.

00:47:45.336 --> 00:47:48.990
But kids, the students,
was my foremost concern.

00:47:48.990 --> 00:47:51.710
They were really like my kids.

00:47:51.710 --> 00:47:54.880
And I felt--
everything about them

00:47:54.880 --> 00:47:58.360
is blurred and edited
out so that you

00:47:58.360 --> 00:48:00.360
can't tell who's who at all.

00:48:00.360 --> 00:48:02.860
Apart from that, when
you read the book,

00:48:02.860 --> 00:48:06.070
the kids come across
loyal to the regime.

00:48:06.070 --> 00:48:08.970
So they're basically
is nothing to fault

00:48:08.970 --> 00:48:12.880
them, as an entire group,
which is how they come across.

00:48:12.880 --> 00:48:14.930
It was hard to do,
because individually, they

00:48:14.930 --> 00:48:16.200
were so adorable.

00:48:16.200 --> 00:48:19.660
And as a writer, doing
characterization,

00:48:19.660 --> 00:48:21.740
there were just little
habits and little sayings,

00:48:21.740 --> 00:48:24.390
little dialogues that happened
there that was just so lovely,

00:48:24.390 --> 00:48:28.225
and I wanted to portray
that unique loveability.

00:48:28.225 --> 00:48:31.090
But, you know, that had to be
sacrificed so that they become

00:48:31.090 --> 00:48:33.970
very blurry, one
group of people,

00:48:33.970 --> 00:48:35.410
who are loyal to the regime.

00:48:35.410 --> 00:48:37.430
So I think I protected them.

00:48:37.430 --> 00:48:39.390
I felt confident with that.

00:48:39.390 --> 00:48:40.482
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:48:40.482 --> 00:48:42.046
INTERVIEWER: Last question.

00:48:42.046 --> 00:48:42.860
AUDIENCE: Hi, Suki.

00:48:42.860 --> 00:48:45.110
Thank you very
much for your talk.

00:48:45.110 --> 00:48:47.326
My question was
regarding something

00:48:47.326 --> 00:48:48.950
you wrote at the
beginning of the book,

00:48:48.950 --> 00:48:52.490
where you said when you came
to New York from South Korea,

00:48:52.490 --> 00:48:54.490
you felt this was not home.

00:48:54.490 --> 00:48:57.300
And then you went back
to South Korea for a bit,

00:48:57.300 --> 00:48:59.570
and you didn't feel
that was home either.

00:48:59.570 --> 00:49:01.070
Did you get some
sense of closure

00:49:01.070 --> 00:49:03.065
from having done this
project to yourself?

00:49:07.340 --> 00:49:09.140
SUKI KIM: Yes and no, I think.

00:49:09.140 --> 00:49:10.840
I think that when
you do lose a home--

00:49:10.840 --> 00:49:15.240
and I think that loss is
something that obviously was

00:49:15.240 --> 00:49:18.740
a motivation for writing
the book, but also

00:49:18.740 --> 00:49:22.430
is a bigger question, even in
the whole history of the two

00:49:22.430 --> 00:49:23.740
Koreas.

00:49:23.740 --> 00:49:27.740
I think when you do
lose home as a child,

00:49:27.740 --> 00:49:30.340
I don't know if you
can get that back.

00:49:30.340 --> 00:49:34.070
But I guess through
writing, you look for it.

00:49:34.070 --> 00:49:37.530
And that search
is a temporary way

00:49:37.530 --> 00:49:41.840
to appease that lost feeling.

00:49:41.840 --> 00:49:43.880
But I'm not sure if I
did get the closure.

00:49:43.880 --> 00:49:48.820
As far as looking for truth
for injustice of that world,

00:49:48.820 --> 00:49:50.940
I think I did get a closure.

00:49:50.940 --> 00:49:54.465
Because it was never
satisfying to go--

00:49:54.465 --> 00:49:56.590
I did cover the New York
Philharmonic in Pyongyang,

00:49:56.590 --> 00:49:58.700
for example.

00:49:58.700 --> 00:50:01.075
There was nothing
to write about that

00:50:01.075 --> 00:50:03.200
unless I wanted to be a
publicist for North Korea's

00:50:03.200 --> 00:50:05.761
regime, which I really
think that's what they want.

00:50:05.761 --> 00:50:07.260
All these articles
about North Korea

00:50:07.260 --> 00:50:09.430
that comes out after
like a three-day trip

00:50:09.430 --> 00:50:11.680
is what I could manage to do.

00:50:11.680 --> 00:50:15.950
But I think by living there and
understanding the place deeper,

00:50:15.950 --> 00:50:18.860
that closure did happen
through this book.

00:50:18.860 --> 00:50:19.990
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:50:19.990 --> 00:50:20.360
INTERVIEWER: Cool.

00:50:20.360 --> 00:50:22.318
Please join me in thanking
Suki Kim for coming.

